In 2002, blood samples from six animals were lost, and hematology data were unavailable for one cat. Various alterations were observed for differential WBC counts in all years of the study. The prevalence of anemic cats among years approached significance (p
 < 0.10). The lowest rate occurred in 2002 (16.2%) and the highest was in 2003 (40.4%) (Table 2
).

Mycoplasma spp. was detected in the colony with significant differences in the prevalence rates among all years (p
 = 0.001), and the percentage of infected animals increased significantly each year (Table 2). Six cats that were negative for Mycoplasma spp. in 2002 tested positive in 2003, and 10 cats negative in 2003 became positive for Mycoplasma spp. in 2004 (Table 3
). One cat negative in 2002 became positive in 2004.
